dataNote: "* In 2020, our mobile forms were re-designed to capture wireless services in three distinct categories; 1. Mobile phone 2. Mobile broadband and 3. Other plans for mobile connected devices.  Only ""Mobile phone"" subscribers were included in this survey.1. ""Mobile phones"" are handheld devices used mainly for voice and data communications, such as smartphones.2. ""Mobile broadband"" revenues and subscribers is defined as tablets, Internet access via netbooks and laptops; exclude mobile handheld devices such as blackberries, iphone, smartphones, etc.3. ""Other plans for mobile connected devices"" should include the number of plans for all other connected peripherials and devices, M2M services (cars, smart meters, trains, consumer electronics/connected ancillary devices) that are not included in or part of the mobile phones and mobile broadband categories. With respect to business subscriptions/accounts that may have multiple unique plans and many connected devices, please report the total number of plans, not the number of connected devices.*** Starting in 2020, only ""mobile phone"" statistics were included."

dataNote: The year saw sustained activity by operators pitching targeted value propositions following the COVID 19 pandemic lockdown in March 2020. Central to these value propositions are Work-From-Home packages as well as streaming services. Some of these players intimated that streaming traffic now accounts for more than 65% of their broadband traffic. In addition, the year witnessed the adoption of mobile money services. As COVID-19 was still very much in the public domain, it hastened the adoption of online and remote working methods. Many retailers and merchants shifted to digital payments over cash due to the reduced risk of exposure.
